  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the most useful tools in a Queensland seller's arsenal is something many vendors have barely heard of until they need it: the backup offer. In simple terms, a backup offer is a second contract that sits behind the primary contract and only comes into effect if the primary contract is terminated. If your buyer's finance falls through, or the building and pest inspection produces a deal-breaker, or the cooling-off period ends badly, your backup offer steps in and, in the best case, you continue to settlement without ever relisting.</p>

      <p>In a strong seller's market, backup offers are not always necessary, because if a contract falls over the property can be remarketed quickly and a new buyer found. In a more balanced or cautious market, however, the difference between having a backup offer in place and not having one can be weeks of additional campaign time, a second round of advertising costs, a weaker negotiating position with the replacement buyer (who will see the failed contract in the portal history), and a materially lower final price. For Brisbane's inner-east market in late 2027, where quality listings still attract multiple interested parties but contract failures do occur, backup offers are worth understanding properly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How a backup offer works in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Under standard Queensland contract practice, when a property goes under contract the agent generally stops marketing the property on a full-press basis. The signs come down from the major portal headlines, open homes stop, and the focus shifts to supporting the primary contract through to settlement. During this period, however, the agent can (and often should) continue to accept written offers from other interested buyers, on the basis that those offers will be held as backup contracts.</p>

      <p>A backup offer in Queensland is typically drafted as a standard REIQ Contract for Houses and Residential Land, with a special condition stating that the contract is conditional on the primary contract being terminated by a specified date. If the primary contract is terminated within that window, the backup contract becomes the primary, and the cooling-off period, finance date, and building and pest date all run from that point. If the primary contract proceeds to settlement, the backup contract simply lapses and the backup buyer walks away without further obligation.</p>

      <p>The key legal point is that a buyer signing a backup offer in Queensland is bound by that offer (subject to the usual cooling-off rights and contract conditions) from the moment both parties sign. They cannot go and sign another contract on a different property assuming the backup will disappear. This means backup buyers need to be genuinely committed, and it also means that a well-drafted backup offer gives a Queensland seller real contractual security, not just a hopeful gesture.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When backup offers are most valuable</h2>
      <p>Not every contract needs a backup. If the primary contract is strong (cash buyer, short settlement, no finance or inspection conditions), the risk of termination is low and a backup may be unnecessary. But for contracts with standard conditions and a typical 30 to 60 day settlement window, there are several situations where a backup offer is particularly worth pursuing.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Finance-conditional contracts.</strong> Queensland's standard contract gives buyers a finance clause window, typically 14 to 21 days, during which they can terminate the contract if finance is not formally approved. In the current lending environment, finance approvals have become more scrutinised and delayed more often. If your primary buyer's finance is not rock-solid, a backup is a sensible safety net.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Building and pest conditional contracts.</strong> Almost every Queensland residential contract is subject to a satisfactory building and pest inspection. The termination right here is broad, and buyers sometimes use the inspection as a renegotiation tool rather than a genuine deal-breaker. If your property is older, has had DIY work done, or is in a flood-affected area, the inspection is a realistic termination risk. A backup gives you leverage in any renegotiation and a clear plan B if the renegotiation fails.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Cooling-off period.</strong> Queensland buyers have a five-business-day cooling-off period on most residential contracts, during which they can terminate for a small penalty (0.25% of the purchase price). Buyers occasionally exercise this right for reasons that have nothing to do with the property: a change in circumstances, cold feet, or a competing property they prefer. A backup offer during the cooling-off window is valuable because the risk is real and the response time is short.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Multiple interested parties at the offer stage.</strong> If your campaign produced more than one serious offer, there is a strong argument for formally capturing the second-best buyer as a backup rather than simply thanking them and letting them walk. A handwritten note or a polite phone call is not a contract; a signed backup offer is. The second buyer is also often willing to match or come close to the primary offer because they have already decided they want the property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The strategic value of telling the primary buyer</h2>
      <p>There is an underappreciated strategic benefit to having a backup offer in place: your primary buyer knows about it. A primary buyer who knows there is a genuine backup behind them is materially less likely to use the finance, inspection, or cooling-off conditions as bargaining chips. They are aware that if they walk, the property moves to the backup buyer and they are out entirely. In a soft market, this can be the difference between a smooth settlement and a mid-contract renegotiation attempt that costs you 3 to 5% of the sale price.</p>

      <p>Queensland agents typically disclose the existence of a backup offer to the primary buyer's solicitor as part of normal contract communication. The identity and terms of the backup are not disclosed, but the existence is. This is standard practice and entirely legitimate; it simply reminds the primary buyer that their contract is not the only option the seller has.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common traps for sellers</h2>
      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Accepting a backup at a price below the primary.</strong> Backups are often written at a slightly lower price than the primary, on the basis that the backup buyer is in a weaker negotiating position (they are, in effect, a fallback rather than a first choice). This is fine as long as you understand the economics: if your primary falls over and the backup steps up, you are accepting that lower price. In a rising market this can sting. In a flat or declining market, accepting a slightly lower backup is usually still better than remarketing.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Not setting clear backup terms.</strong> A backup contract needs a clear trigger mechanism and a clear expiry. If the primary contract is terminated on day 21 of a 30 day settlement, when does the backup's cooling-off period start? When does their finance clock begin? These details need to be in the special conditions, and a solicitor should draft them properly. A vague backup contract can produce its own disputes.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Forgetting about disclosure obligations.</strong> Under Queensland's 2025 statutory disclosure regime, the Form 2 disclosure statement and prescribed certificates need to be given to the backup buyer before they sign the backup contract, just as they would for a primary contract. Sellers sometimes assume the backup is a less formal arrangement and skip this step. It is not. The same disclosure rules apply, and the same termination rights flow to the backup buyer if disclosure is defective.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Accepting too many backups.</strong> In theory a seller can accept multiple backup offers, each stacked behind the last. In practice, this creates administrative complexity and can produce conflicts between backup buyers if the primary contract falls through late. A single well-qualified backup is almost always better than three weakly qualified ones.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Continuing to market aggressively while under contract.</strong> Once a primary contract is signed, the agent should shift to a backup-only marketing mode: inquiries are handled, but open homes stop and major advertising pauses. Some sellers push agents to keep marketing aggressively on the hope of collecting more backups. This is usually counterproductive, because it sends the message that the primary contract is weak and it can actually unsettle the primary buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pricing a backup offer</h2>
      <p>Backup offers typically come in 2 to 8% below the primary contract price in Queensland, depending on how interested the backup buyer is and how much leverage they believe they have. As a seller, you need to think clearly about your reserve: if the primary falls over, what is the minimum price you would accept to avoid relisting? In most cases, the remarketing cost plus the reputational impact of a failed contract is worth 3 to 5% of the original price, so accepting a backup within that range is often a rational decision.</p>

      <p>The opposite situation occurs in competitive markets where a backup buyer desperately wants the property. In those cases, the backup offer can actually match or exceed the primary, and the seller has a genuinely valuable safety net. If the primary falls over, the seller moves to a slightly higher price without going back to market. This is rare, but it does happen, particularly in suburbs where quality listings are scarce.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to handle the primary buyer</h2>
      <p>A subtle point that experienced sellers and agents get right: once you accept a backup, the primary buyer's experience should not change in any visible way. They should not feel pressured or threatened. They should not receive passive-aggressive communications hinting that someone else is waiting in the wings. The backup is a legal and commercial safety net, not a negotiating weapon. Good agents make sure the primary feels valued and supported through to settlement, regardless of what is happening behind the scenes. The best outcome for everyone is the primary contract settling smoothly, with the backup quietly lapsing.</p>

      <p>If the primary contract does hit trouble (finance extension request, renegotiation attempt after inspection, or a request to extend settlement), the existence of a backup gives you confidence to hold a firm position. Without a backup, sellers are often pushed into concessions that materially reduce their result. With a backup, you can say no to an unreasonable request, knowing you have a clear alternative.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When not to bother with backups</h2>
      <p>Backup offers have a cost, even if that cost is mostly in agent and solicitor time. If your primary contract is strong (cash buyer, short settlement, minimal conditions, large deposit) and the market is active, the chances of the primary falling over are low and the marginal value of a backup is small. In those cases, the agent can simply keep warm contact with other interested parties without formal backup contracts, on the basis that if something does go wrong, those buyers can be re-engaged quickly.</p>

      <p>Similarly, if your property is the kind of listing that draws strong demand (a well-presented home in a tightly-held suburb with few comparable listings), the risk of needing to remarket is low and the cost of doing so is manageable. In those situations, a backup is an optional belt-and-braces approach rather than a necessity.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bottom line for Queensland sellers</h2>
      <p>Backup offers are a quietly powerful tool in the Queensland contract process, and they are particularly valuable when the primary contract is conditional, when the market is balanced or cautious, or when your campaign produced more than one serious buyer. A well-drafted backup, supported by proper statutory disclosure, provides real contractual security without disturbing the primary buyer's progress toward settlement. A poorly drafted one, or an overcomplicated backup arrangement with multiple parties, can produce its own problems. Get the drafting right with a Queensland-experienced solicitor, keep the primary buyer's experience smooth, and use the backup as what it is: a safety net that you hope you never need to catch you, but that is genuinely reassuring to have in place.</p>

      <p>For a typical Brisbane inner-east house sale, the decision to pursue a backup offer is worth a 15 minute conversation with your agent after your primary contract is signed. If the primary is strong, you may conclude a backup is unnecessary. If there are known risks (finance stretched, old structure, flood history), a backup is almost always worth the effort. Either way, the decision should be deliberate, not accidental.</p>

